Sunday
is
God's
day
in
Whitcomb,
Indiana.
The
summer
sun
slaps

heat
upon
it,
presses
down
broad
sheets
of
heat
to
lie
on
the
flat
fields
of

goldening
grain
which
fringe
it.
But
Whitcomb,
nerveless
and
tired,
lies

on
the
prairie
like
a
thing
relaxed,
empty
of
troubles
for
a
time
under
the

sky
of
God
and
in
his
presence.
A
rhythmic
silence,
rising
from
its
quietness,

softly
accents
its
mood
of
peace.
Peace
wraps
Whitcomb
and
those
who

live
there,
and
draws
them
to
a
union
with
the
peace
of
God.

Wayne
Street
lies
resting
in
Whitcomb.
Like
a
pavement
flooring

a
streak
of
sky,
it
stretches
through
Whitcomb
between
two
rows
of
homes

and
shops:
incurious,
passive,
glaringly
white,
it
lies
relaxed
and
silent.

Four
stores,
out
of
the
four
blocks
of
shops
which
line
it,
are
open
on

Sunday;
these
are
the
three
Drug
Stores,
and
the
fourth
is
Frank's
Smoke
House.

Inside
Frank's
Smoke
House,
up
in
the
front
around
the
soft
drinks

fountain,
some
men
are
standing
in
a
ragged
spread
of
tobacco
smoke.
The

smoke
is
a
screen
which
shields
an
anger:
anger
like
an
impersonal
force;

anger
maintaining
the
peace
of
Whitcomb;
dynamic
anger
whirring;
twisting

the
current
it
generates
from
one
mind
to
another
in
the
torn
smoke.
